<dl id="n01006b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01006b">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01006b"> 6(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ runs down wind <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n01006b"><li>FW 476.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n01006b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n01006b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n01006b">MS BL 47482b-63</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:005 <a name="rA1d" href="../../ff/fdra/rda.htm#rA1d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/r/rA1d.htm#n01006b">Draft: III&sect;3A.1</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When hunted, <font color="green">[the fox]</font> cares little about being able to see or hear his pursuers as long as he can wind them. Thus he is never content unless well to leeward of the hounds; <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is for this reason, of course, that he habitually <mark>runs down wind</mark> <small> Douglas Gordon, <a name="GDRF" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#GDRF"><cite title="source">&ldquo;Reynard the Fox&rdquo;</cite></a>, <cite a>Quarterly Review</cite></a> (October 1922) 273</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
